WEBVTT

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:02.706
A green checkmark feels comforting in
software

00:00:03.633 --> 00:00:08.581
It says the build passed The tests passed
The

00:00:08.594 --> 00:00:12.448
robot is happy And when you are tired it
is easy

00:00:12.474 --> 00:00:15.938
to read that as a bigger sentence This is
safe

00:00:15.964 --> 00:00:19.167
to merge But a green check usually means

00:00:19.193 --> 00:00:22.956
something narrower It means this check
passed on

00:00:22.982 --> 00:00:26.302
this version under these conditions That
is

00:00:26.328 --> 00:00:29.544
useful evidence It is not a verdict

00:00:30.602 --> 00:00:32.972
Use three questions to keep the signal in
its

00:00:32.998 --> 00:00:37.141
lane Fresh base Right diff

00:00:38.052 --> 00:00:39.250
Uncovered risk

00:00:40.274 --> 00:00:43.961
First Fresh base Did the check run against
the

00:00:43.974 --> 00:00:47.529
target you are about to merge or deploy
into In

00:00:47.542 --> 00:00:50.198
a fast-moving repo the target branch can
move

00:00:50.224 --> 00:00:53.297
while a pull request waits The check may
have

00:00:53.323 --> 00:00:56.656
been true when main looked one way Then
other

00:00:56.682 --> 00:01:01.162
work lands The surrounding file changes A

00:01:01.188 --> 00:01:04.990
validator appears A slot that was empty
becomes

00:01:05.016 --> 00:01:09.833
occupied The old check is not useless But
it is

00:01:09.846 --> 00:01:13.675
dated evidence In one exploratory AI
Village

00:01:13.701 --> 00:01:16.214
pull-request study local git
reconstruction

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:19.781
covered six hundred and ten pull requests
One

00:01:19.807 --> 00:01:22.307
hundred forty-four heads were not
descendants of

00:01:22.333 --> 00:01:25.641
their recorded base That does not prove
those

00:01:25.654 --> 00:01:28.896
branches were unsafe It does mean the base

00:01:28.922 --> 00:01:32.490
relationship was a useful place to look
Green on

00:01:32.516 --> 00:01:36.565
an old base is not bad evidence It is old
evidence

00:01:37.576 --> 00:01:41.044
Second Right diff Did the check inspect
the

00:01:41.068 --> 00:01:44.753
exact change that will land A file list is
not

00:01:44.779 --> 00:01:48.151
the same as today's merge diff A preview
from

00:01:48.177 --> 00:01:51.836
memory is not the same as today's merge
diff In

00:01:51.849 --> 00:01:54.583
the same study's case appendix one pull
request

00:01:54.609 --> 00:01:57.005
was described as mechanically mergeable
with

00:01:57.031 --> 00:02:00.391
passing checks A reviewer noted a narrower

00:02:00.417 --> 00:02:03.854
problem The diff inserted new entries
before an

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:07.526
already-merged tail That shifted the
intended

00:02:07.552 --> 00:02:11.263
numbering It did not append after current
main

00:02:12.188 --> 00:02:14.375
The issue was not simply whether the code
could

00:02:14.401 --> 00:02:17.526
parse The issue was whether the checked
change

00:02:17.552 --> 00:02:20.990
matched the real review question So do not
only

00:02:21.016 --> 00:02:24.310
ask whether a check passed Ask what diff
the

00:02:24.336 --> 00:02:25.547
check was attached to

00:02:26.584 --> 00:02:30.297
Third Uncovered risk What important
failure

00:02:30.323 --> 00:02:33.474
could still happen if the check is right
Some

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:35.935
failures are easy for generic automation
to see

00:02:36.117 --> 00:02:38.997
the file does not compile the unit test
fails a

00:02:38.995 --> 00:02:42.237
required command exits with an error Other

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:45.453
failures are about meaning Did this remove

00:02:45.479 --> 00:02:48.735
recent work Did it preserve the source
layout

00:02:48.761 --> 00:02:51.664
the application expects Did it change

00:02:51.677 --> 00:02:54.752
permissions ordering user-visible wording
or a

00:02:54.737 --> 00:02:58.318
hidden invariant The most useful question
is not

00:02:58.513 --> 00:03:01.964
Did the robot approve It is What would
still

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:03.643
worry me if the robot is right

00:03:04.672 --> 00:03:08.541
This is also the caveat A stale branch is
not

00:03:08.567 --> 00:03:12.396
automatically unsafe A large deletion
count is

00:03:12.422 --> 00:03:16.198
not automatically bad And a passing check
is not

00:03:16.224 --> 00:03:20.898
automatically enough Each of those is a
signal not a verdict

00:03:21.928 --> 00:03:24.233
So before you treat a green check as
approval

00:03:24.428 --> 00:03:27.959
ask Fresh base did the check run against
the

00:03:27.972 --> 00:03:31.500
target I am about to merge or deploy into
Right

00:03:31.527 --> 00:03:34.144
diff did it inspect the exact change that
will

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:38.063
land Uncovered risk what important failure
could

00:03:38.089 --> 00:03:40.042
still happen if this check is correct

00:03:41.056 --> 00:03:43.621
If you are using an AI assistant during
review

00:03:43.843 --> 00:03:47.399
ask it the same thing What version base
branch

00:03:47.621 --> 00:03:50.785
and diff did this check run on What files

00:03:50.915 --> 00:03:54.834
behaviors or risks did it not inspect What
human

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.217
decision remains even if the check result
is

00:03:57.230 --> 00:04:00.550
correct That prompt cannot make the
decision

00:04:00.576 --> 00:04:03.897
safe But it can slow the moment down so
the

00:04:03.923 --> 00:04:05.290
evidence stays visible

00:04:06.348 --> 00:04:11.116
Keep the green check It is useful Just
read it

00:04:11.142 --> 00:04:15.530
like a receipt What version did it check
What

00:04:15.556 --> 00:04:19.045
diff did it inspect What risk did it leave

00:04:19.072 --> 00:04:22.144
uncovered Let the green check speed up the

00:04:22.157 --> 00:04:25.582
review Do not let it replace the question
